Smart move. Keeping the ChatGPT-powered chatbot out of the MVP (Minimum Viable Product) but in your Future Work/Scalability section is the perfect "academic balance." It shows you have a high-level vision without overcomplicating your initial development.
How to document this in your paper:
1. In the Methodology (The "Scalability" Section)
Explain that while the MVP uses keyword-based bilingual search (mapping "Room" and "Chambre" to the same database category), the architecture is designed to integrate an LLM (Large Language Model) API like GPT-4 via a middleware layer.
Why wait? You can justify this by citing the need to first establish a clean data baseline and minimize API costs/latency for the initial user rollout in Cameroon.
2. In the Socio-Economic Impact (The "Inclusive" Argument)
This is where the chatbot shines. A voice-to-text GPT bot allows low-literacy workers (e.g., a plumber who may struggle with typing) to describe their service in Cameroon Pidgin or spoken French. The AI can then "translate" that into a structured listing.
Source: Mention the OpenAI API Documentation as the technical foundation for this future integration.
3. The "Data Analytics" Connection
Mention that the search logs you are collecting now will serve as the Training/Fine-tuning Data for that future AI. By logging how people actually search for houses in Douala or Yaoundé (using local slang or specific quarter names), you are building the specific "Cameroon Context" that a generic AI lacks.
The "WhatsApp + GPT" Power Move
In your "Future Work" section, describe a flow where a user can simply send a WhatsApp Voice Note like: "I de look for room for Molyko below 30k."
The system uses the Whisper API (audio-to-text) + GPT to extract the city, budget, and type.
It then queries your database and sends the top 3 WhatsApp contact links back to the user.
