To make this look professional for your graduation committee, use the following draft. It highlights that you aren't just using AI because it's "trendy," but because it solves a specific accessibility problem for the Cameroon context.
Future Work: Enhancing Accessibility via LLM Integration
"While the current MVP (Minimum Viable Product) utilizes a structured bilingual search architecture, the system is designed for horizontal scalability through the integration of Large Language Models (LLMs) such as GPT-4. Future iterations will implement a conversational AI agent to bridge the digital literacy gap among informal workers and house hunters in Cameroon.
By leveraging the OpenAI API, the platform will transition from keyword-matching to Natural Language Processing (NLP), allowing users to submit queries in Cameroon Pidgin or regional dialects via WhatsApp voice notes. This is particularly critical for the socio-economic inclusion of workers with limited formal education. The system will utilize the Whisper model for speech-to-text conversion, followed by GPT-driven entity extraction to identify specific user needs (e.g., 'budget,' 'location,' and 'service type').
Furthermore, the search logs captured during the MVP phase will provide the necessary localized dataset to fine-tune these models, ensuring the AI understands regional nuances—such as specific 'quarter' names and local pricing slang—that generic models currently lack. This evolution will transform the platform from a directory into a fully inclusive, voice-activated digital concierge for the informal economy."
Key Phrases to Emphasize in Your Presentation:
"Digital Concierge": It sounds more high-end and helpful than just a "bot."
"Entity Extraction": This is the technical term for the AI "picking out" the city and price from a messy sentence.
"Localized Dataset": This proves why your platform is better for Cameroon than a global app—you have the local data.
